caption:
Let me blow your mind 🤯🤯🤯
.
.
Purposeful exercise is NOT enough. 🙈
.
.
What makes up the body's need for energy? (Aproximations) ⚡ 60% BMR - this rate is affected by genetics, environment, food consumption, overall activity etc
⚡ 10% TEF - this is the energy we need to breakdown and absorb food. Certain foods like protein rich foods have a high thermic effect, therefore eating more of them results in higher TEF.
⚡20% NEAT - This is the exercise we do involuntarily like walking, housework, gardening or playing with kids.
⚡10% Purposeful Exercise
.
.
Let's say Sarah is trying to lose X kg. Sarah  is 87kg and has been highly inactive her whole life. Her diet is and always has been highly processed. She works a desk job and her family have 'always carried a few pounds'. So Sarah starts resistance training 4 times a week. But she is still sedentary outside of those 4 sessions. And she hasn't cleaned up her diet....what do you think will happen? Sarah will seriously struggle to lose weight 😔
.
Eileen on the other hand is 67kg and back to the gym twice a week after having a baby. She trained 4 times a week up until having Thomas. She has always had a healthy lifestyle which she maintained while pregnant and breastfeeding. Her diet is protein rich with lots of fruit and vegetables and the odd treat 😜 She plays with Thomas daily...
Will it be easier for Eileen even though she has less weight to lose?
Absolutely 👌👌👌
.
.
Purposeful exercise is great and should be part of a weekly routine. But it is only a very small piece of the puzzle. Don't forget what we put in our mouths has a huge impact on our BMR and burns energy through TEF. NEAT is often over looked and has more impact on TDEE than Purposeful exercise. It's a much larger picture than 'just going to the gym'. #tdee #neatup #tef #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitliving #fitlifestyle #fitfam #healthylifestyle #healthiswealth #irishfitfam

People often ask me what exercise is 'best for your bum', 'how do I get rid of love handles', or 'can you target my bingo wings'. Unfortunately, we cannot spot reduce🙈 If it were that easy we'd all be walking around with 'perfect' bodies 😜
.
.
But if there was one exercise I would recommend it would be the Deadlift 🙂 It is a compound movement that really hits many muscle groups 💪 Unfortunately, it is often executed incorrectly and is almost always recommended by health professionals to 'stay away from' if they have injuries. Which is such a pity because if executed properly it can actually help strengthen muscle groups and reduce the incidence of injury 😔
.
.
I have demonstrated 4 different types of Deadlifts. There are more. Some may have to adjust for lever length or injury etc. But the main take home points of a Deadlift.
➡️ Hip hinge. If you can master this movement. You have mastered a lot of the exercise and many other exercises. I recommend practising with a dowel until fully comfortable with this position.
➡️ 3 points of contact. If you were to put a dowl on your back it should touch your head, in between shoulder blades and glutes. If one is not in position, your position is not correct.
➡️ Slow and controlled movement. Make sure not to Jerk the weight.
Point to note. Remember, we have muscles in our lower back so if you have a little bit of pain following Deadlifts it may often be DOMS. Don't automatically think the worst. But if the problem persists, seek professional help. I would always recommend to get a qualified trainer or physio to watch your form before executing Deadlifts 👌

caption:
Let's talk disordered eating ⚠️⚠️⚠️
.
.
I've always said I've never had an eating disorder e.g anoxeria, bulimia. But that doesn't mean I've never had disordered eating. An eating disorder sometimes doesn't capture the full range of complexity of people's eating experiences 🤔🤔🤔
.
.
Unfortunately, most people in their lifetime will have some sort of disordered eating. Even those that think they don't 😔 With the society we live in these days, this has become even more prevalent. The strive for perfection in everything we do has become extreme. The pressure to look a certain way. It's no wonder everyone has a form of disordered eating 😔
.
.
So what kind of behaviours fall into the Disordered Eating (DE) category:
👉 Restriction and tight control of food
👉 Routines and rules are food (certain foods are 'BAD' or when someone should eat)
👉 Bingeing
👉 Compensation for binging - purging, over exercise, fasting
👉Anxiety and Avoidance - eating out, social events etc
👉 Orthorexia - obsession with healthy eating
👉 Body Dysmorphia - distorted body image
.
.
Sadly, I can safely say in my lifetime I have experienced ALL of the above😔 And I'm sure I'm not alone.
.
.
I will not say I'm 110% body confident or happy all the time but thankfully I am rid of my disordered eating. It's not easy. It takes a lot of self acceptance. It takes talking - be that to a friend, family member, counsellor. It takes accepting there is an underlying issue and this behaviour is as a result of that. Its not easy but it can be done 💕
.
.
Let's try and be kind to ourselves, each other and our bodies 🙏

#disorderedeating #talktosomeone #itsoknottobeok #loveyourself #loveyourbody #healthiswealth #health #healthylifestyle #healthyliving #fitliving #fitlifestyle #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitfam #irishfitfam

Protein is a vital part of every diet no matter what your goals. 💯
.
.
I am a huge fan of plant based diets. I am not vegetarian but I try to get a large amount of plants into my diet. It was often thought that vegetarians don't get enough protein in their diet. Vegetarians can get a sufficient amount of protein in their diet with good meal planning and preparation. But eliminating any part of your diet can come with trade offs so it is important there is a conscious effort to add protein to all meals. There is also risk of deficiencies such as iron and Vitamin B12 so air on the side of caution⚠️⚠️⚠️
.
.
Variety is the spice of life 🍳🌰🥛 #vegetarian #proteinsources #protein #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitlife #fitliving #fitlifestyle #healthylifestyle #healthyliving #fitfam #irishfitfam

caption:
I know how to get more followers...
.
.
I know that I could do my hair nicer. I know I could paint on some make up and do my tan more. I know I could pose for photos and show off my waist to hip ratio (I'd be well able, it's fairly sustantial😂). I know I could diet a little and have visible abs (actually all I'd need is a little water and carb manipulation and they'd be visible). I know I could buy followers. I could throw myself at brands and ask them for discount codes and #sp.
.
.
But none of that is me ❎❎❎
.
.
I have had the word 'role model' thrown at me lately. A LOT. ❤️ I have heard the words 'real', 'normal' and 'healthy' being used to describe me. And not to forget 'fit'. Because that's what I am. Fit. I'm not a model. (Far from it 😂). There is nothing about me fake. I don't even know how to use these apps that change how you look 🤣🤣🤣
.
.
This page was set up to keep me accountable. That it has. I don't really need that anymore it's part of my life.
✔️I now use it to try and give a little nutrition and training information.
✔️I use it to talk - It's my way of blowing out. If I'm happy. If I'm upset. If I'm angry. It's my platform to display my feelings ❤️ ❤️ ❤️
✔️ I use it to show all parts of my life. Which in recent times has actually been so fun-filled and action packed🏖️🌏✈️
✔️ I use it to be real - Social media has become so fake.
.
I may not have a serious amount of followers but at least every person who follows me wanted to. 🤔🤔🤔 #fitliving #fitlife #fitlifestyle #fitfam #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #healthylifestyle #healthiswealth #healthyliving #fitfam #irishfitfam

caption:
Pull it back 🔙🔙🔙
.
.
Sometimes I think people (myself included) give all this 'great' information on macronutrients and some people don't even know what a 'carb' source is 🙈
.
.
This is a great diagram to show what foods contain what. Some foods are primarily single nutrient based while others contain more than one.
.
.
I use this a lot when I talk about carb or calorie cycling. I also use it in relation to trying to keep treat meals within your goals.
E.G If going out for a meal but weight loss is a goal and you don't want to absolutely ruin all progress. I would recommend to a client stick to either a protein/fat OR protein/cárb meal. Yes, it comes down to overall calories but it's much easier to overeat on a protein/fat/carb meal like a lasagne and chips than a steak and veg or a stir fry with rice 🤔
.
.
Hope this helps clear up some things for people 😃
.
.

caption:
I had a little giggle with one of my friends the other day about how different my page has become since we first met which was about 5 years ago (when I first started this) She had actually been following me and we ended up working together and it blossomed after that. Cute I know ❤️
.
.
I have learned so much in that 5 years. I have educated myself so much more. I have made mistakes which I've learned from. I tried some silly things and failed. But also tried some crazy things and succeeded 🙌 My page is a reflection of what I do, it always has been. It was started to keep me accountable 🙈😂 If I didn't have thousands of bloody posts I'd definitely be looking back cringing 😂🙈 As you get older, you do learn, you do get some Sense, you do find yourself. 👌
.
.
5 years ago the girl writing posts on this page was: Insecure, searching for abs, weaker - physically & mentally and enjoying exercise but also punishing herself for a binge the odd time
.
.
Now, this girl is: Confident, enjoys every time she exercises (no punishment workouts required), body composition is not my goal (although my body is in great shape, it is as a result of training hard, it's not my priority, its as a by product) and I am so proud of what my body is capable of ❤️
.
.
Love your body. Love what your body is capable of. Stop searching for aesthetic goals. Start focusing on performance. Embrace everything your body CAN do. Nourish your body. You're going to be in it your whole life, you might aswell start looking after it 🙌🙌🙌
.
.
P. S this video was the round from hell. Final wod was: 11,9,7,5 Cál Row, Thrusters, Hanging Knee Raises & BBJO

caption:
Food Prep 🍲🍽️
.
.
Fail to prepare, prepare to fail ☢️☢️☢️
.
.
We all have the same 24 hours in the day. Yes, it's very easy to be 'too busy' to prepare and cook food. A takeaway or a deli are very appealing after a long day of work. But it comes down to habit. If you form a habit, this becomes a lot easier.
If you keep putting it on the back burner it becomes harder. 🙄
.
.
My top tips to Food Prep:
- Do a weekly food shop - Having good foods in the house make it easier. If you have no food in your fridge it's much easier to pick up convenience crap. Do a full shop at the start of the week and you're off to a great start😉 The above ingredients are the basis of my food shop every week 📃
.
- Pick a day. Take an hour and get prepping. I do a Sunday evening. I put a batch of chicken, fish and turkey burgers in the oven to last me 3 days. While they are cooking, I boil broccoli and make up a salad. I chop up my fruit and portion out my Greek yogurt. I put my overnight oats in the fridge for the next day. It take me and hour to get the bulk of my food ready for 3 days. I use microwaveable rice to save time too. I save money because I rarely eat out and make all my own lunches. I do the same on a Wednesday evening. Tupperware is your new best friend. .
- Find food you like and stick with it. It's actually very simple. People overcomplicate it. It's unnecessary.
.
- If you do have to eat out or buy lunch there are LOADS of healthy options. Stop saying there's none. Go to Aldi, buy a bag of spinach, hot smoked salmon and a pot of cous cous (portion out). That's 2 lunches. Stop using excuses
.
- Get into a routine. I am in such a routine now that even when I go off course like have a few drinks at the weekend, I am back to Tupperware on Monday. Its ALL ABOUT HABITS 👌
.
.
Let me know some of your food prep ideas 🤔 Mine are pretty monotonous. It's really just about forming a habit and sticking to it 👌

#eatforhealth #eatforperformance #foodprep #fitlifestyle #fitliving #healthylifestyle #fitfam #irishfitfam

Searching for motivation 🔎🔎🔎
.
.
Most people think motivation should come naturally and then you'll form a habit. When in fact it's the other way around. Motivation is a result of habits formed. You don't just wake up one day and say that's it, I'm gonna be motivated for good 😏 It just doesn't happen like that. Your habits create motivation. People always ask me how am I so motivated all the time 🤔
.
.
Firstly, know that I am not motivated all the time. No one is. But training regularly and eating healthy are both habits to me. I don't go through periods of eating well and exercising. I do it regularly and consistently. How are some people so 'motivated' to go out every weekend? Habit..What about people who play football every weekend? Habit (they also have responsibility to a coach and a team) which brings me onto my next point.
.
.
I advise getting a coach. Someone who holds you accountable. It's not always easy at the start. It can take a long time to form a habit. Having a coach there, helps you from quitting when you want to(and there will be times you want to)
.
.
Stop focusing on the end goal and start enjoying the ride 🚲 This one I can't emphasise enough. Today was my first day off training in 13 days. I really really wanted to train (I love training) but it was more important to get a day out with my family. It should add to your life, not take away from it. Sometimes it will be priority, sometimes it won't but you need to incorporate it into your lifestyle and make time for it. ✌️
.
.
Remember, you are in control. You decide what you can and can't do. Goals are important. But stop focusing so much on an end point and enjoy the journey 👌Oh and find something you enjoy, that is vital. If you don't enjoy it, you won't sustain it 😔😖 #motivation #youareincontrol #takecontrol #goals #fitliving #fitlifestyle #fitness #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitfam #irishfitfam

Snack options 🤔
.
.
One of my most frequently asked questions 🤔 I feel like people want 1 million different options 😂 When they can actually build snacks simply around 1 food 😀
.
.
Option 1 : Tuna - can be eaten alone, can be mixed with cottage cheese, can be added to Corncakes, can be added to a green salad. There's 4 different snacks with just tuna
.
.
Option 2: Greek yogurt - add berries, add an orange, add grapes, add Choc shot, add granola, add nut butter... The list goes on.
.
.
Option 3: The old reliable. Apple and nut butter 😍 Be cautious of nut butter allowance 👌
.
.
Option 4: Nuts - again jam packed full of nutrients but be careful of portion size as these calories can accumulate
.
.
Option 5: Oatcakes/Corncakes/Ricecakes - Add a little nut butter, normal butter, cheese, Choc shot, fruit... The list is endless ✌️
.
.
Other options include: Fruit, Veg with hummus, boiled eggs, protein shakes, protein bars. There is a huge variety. If you like the odd treat opt for crisps or sweets with less than 100 Cals 😜
.
.
I'd love to know your GO TO snacks

Weights can make you bulky 😬😬😬
.
.
OK, now I've got your attention. Let me explain to you 😝
.
.
2014 This was me: 9 stone of skin and bone, Active my whole life with a poor diet and a little pot belly 🐤😂 I had no upper body strength. I could not lift more than a 7kg bar overhead. Please don't use 'not being able to do a pull up' as a measure of upper body strength, they are damn bloody hard 😩 And A lot of super strong people can't do them.
.
.
Fast forward 5 years later. I am 10.5 stone with a heck of a lot of that muscle and a little chub 😉🐷 I eat to fuel my body and I still have my protruding stomach but it's leaner 😂😋
.
.
So why do I reckon I gained so much weight?
I genuinely think people look at me and think, ah she looked better before she started weight training. And that's fine. That's people's opinions and they are entitled to that. But I gained muscle. I added about 40kg to my overhead press and my legs and bum make up 3/4 of my weight I reckon 😂 But this doesn't just happen overnight and probably won't happen to many people. I train very regularly and consistently usually 5/6 times a week, sometimes twice a day. That sheer volume will of course increase muscle mass. And I eat to maintain.
.
.
If you train like me, and depending on your size and frame, there is a possibility you will gain weight. Your size 8 pants may jump to a size 10 😳😂 But chances are you don't train like me and if you did, you wouldn't be caring about a little weight gain 🤷‍♀️
. .
I can promise doing 3 45 min weight sessions a week will NOT make you 'bulky'. It will however:
☑️ Help you drop body fat
☑️ Improve your overall body composition, ☑️ Make you stronger,
☑️ Improve bone Density
☑️ Strengthen joints, tendons and ligaments
☑️ Make you happier and healthier

#weighttraining #strengthtraining #weighttrainladies #weights #bulky #strongwomen #fitliving #fitlifestyle #fitfam #irishfitfam

This is probably one of my most honest posts I've EVER wrote. And that's saying something 🙈Because I'm pretty much an open book 📙 Some of you might agree with me. Most of you won't. It's an opinion that is all 😇
.
.
I lost my love of football about 3 years ago 💔💔💔
.
.
When I first started, skill was priority. Which I had none of 😂 But I still had the craic. It was so much fun. Even though I never got a game, the sidelines were hopping when I was around 🎶🎶🎶
Between the ages of 18 and 25, fitness was priority 🏃‍♀️Finally my lucky break 🙌 I may not be able to kick a ball, but I was fit 🙋💪 I enjoyed football so much during these years ❤️ And thankfully, they were my best years performance wise and I had a few medals to show for it too 🏅🏅🏅
.
.
But the last 3 years the game has changed. Or maybe it was just my mentality. I had sacrificed so much for so long, maybe I was just sick of doing that 🤔 Or maybe I just don't have the same winning mentality others have. 🤷‍♀️ I cannot do 'whatever it takes' to win. Its just not in me 🚫 And as for sacrifice. It used to be a 2 week drinking ban which has now turned into: No holidays, no alcohol for months, no social life, strain on relationships/friendships.
.
.
So why do you still do it?
The girls ❤️ The friends you make and the relationships you build make it all worthwhile. That being said I am done at intercounty level. I want to enjoy engagements, weddings, and 30ths. I've had my time. I've lost a lot more than I've won, but I'm happy to call quits on my inter County career now. I don't get the same thrill as I used to. I'm slowing down and I'm enjoying other things more (club and crossfit) 💪
.
.
Thanks to all the amazing people I've met along the way. All the people who've injured me. All the people I've injured. All part of the journey. .
.
See ya in the County Final xo

.
.
No matter what it's in relation to. Whether it's fitness, lifestyle, new foods, meeting new people, changing career, moving, education... The list goes on 📃 Great things happen in your growth and learning zone 👌
.
.
I'm normally pretty good for veering outside my comfort zone. I'm constantly pushing myself fitness wise. I'm always trying to further my education and knowledge. I'm great for trying new foods and visiting new places 🏖️
.
.
But this pushed me out of my comfort zone. Firstly, the idea of photos alone makes my skin Crawl (selfies don't count, there's just something different🙈). Secondly, I am OCD about organisation. So when I had to get these photos unorganised I freaked 😬😬😬 It was a Friday morning. I had been up since 5 and forgot Gym gear, make up and to brush me hair 😭 I was pasty and had my period ☹️ I had a day to prepare for these pictures so needless to say there was no 'photoshoot prep' 😔😔😔 But I did it. And I didn't die of embarrassment 😂 I was actually pretty happy with the interview in the magazine (which the photos were for). It was absolutely fine 😂 It's great to get out of that comfort zone every once and everything worked out OK in the end 🙌 Thanks @michellehugheswalshphotography 😁 And today, I decided to sign up to a crossfit competition totally untrained 😂

caption:
Is brown or basmati rice better? 🤔
.
.
Another nutrition answer that people don't like to hear but it depends 🙈😂 (Anwser to almost every nutrition related question😂). Well that's mainly because there are no 'good' or 'bad' foods and that question is too generic.
.
.
Picture 2 gives a nutritional break down of basmati rice while picture 3 is Brown rice's nutrition composition. Calories from basmati rice are slightly higher than brown rice while the protein content is also slightly higher. Brown rice is slightly higher in fat. Both have similar fibre content and both have a medium GI.
.
.
So really as you can see there is no dramatic nutritional difference between both grains. Basmati Rice may be slightly easier to digest than brown rice but that varies from person to person. I personally recommend variety. I also recommend convenience and what fits into your lifestyle (personally boiling brown rice for 30 mins doesn't fit into my lifestyle and a microwave basmati is much more convenient). I wouldn't fret over which one is 'better' but rather have both. Also, if you're picking either over chips you're doing something right 🙌🙏 #nutrition #nutritionfacts #realnutrition #realfood #alwayslearning #healthyliving #healthylifestyle #fitliving #fitlifestyle #fitfam #irishfitfam

For the day that's in it 📜📜📜
.
.
Here's my story:
I stressed so much over that bloody Leaving Cert. My hair fell out. I looked like a skeleton. And we won't even get started on my face make up less 😂 And for what 🤷‍♀️ I ended up with a great Leaving Cert. Got the course I wanted 💯❤️ Studied in UCD for 4 years it was all fantastic 😀 Until I got out of college, there were no jobs. I went back to the job I worked in throughout school and college. 🔙 After a year, I decided I needed to use my Nutrition degree and with the lack of the jobs in the area I decided to go into personal training and fitness instruction 💡💡💡
The course was fantastic. I was delighted with it. It was a full time course so I was on the dole. I finished it and was all set to start my career when.... I tore my ACL. Bear in mind I had not been working prior to this and with course fees I was pretty much broke 😩 So €7000 worth of surgery, scans and doctors appointments later. I was now an unfit, useless personal trainer with debt up to my eyeballs 😬
.
.
5 years later... I'm doing pretty alright. I'm in a job and career I absolutely ADORE. I've had a few magazine and news paper articles. I've been an ambassador and role model. I've worked with successful teams and its only going to get better. I'm still building on my knowledge. 10 years after sitting my leaving cert I'm finally settled. Will I be in this industry forever? 🤔 I don't know. It took me a long enough to get here so I'm just going to enjoy the ride. 🚲 There are ways to achieve your career. Long roads🚜 Short Paths🚴 But you can and will get there with a little determination 💯❤️ #leavingcert #lifegoeson #dontletapieceofpaperdefineyourlife

What is iron and why is it important?
.
. 
Iron is an essential mineral needed by the body. Its primary function is to transport oxygen in the haemoglobin of red blood cells so the cells can produce energy. It also helps to remove carbon dioxide.
. 
How much iron do you need and where do we get it?
.
. 
Infants and toddlers need more iron than adults because their bodies are still growing. Women need more iron than men due to menstruation. Women require about 18mg/day while men need just 8mg/day. Iron is found in foods like: Shellfish, Liver, Red Meat, Spinach, Kale and Fortified Cereals. Haem Iron is the iron we get from animal sources and is most easily absorbed in the body. Non haem iron comes from plant sources and is not as easily absorbed so may require supplementation in vegetarians and vegans. Vitamin C is also essential for Iron absorption. It’s found in many fruits like Blackcurrants, strawberries, kiwis and oranges. Adding orange juice or fruit to an iron rich meal can help absorption.
.
. 
How do I know if I’m deficient in Iron?
.
. 
Common symptoms of Iron deficiency anaemia include: Fatigue, Paleness, Difficulty exercising, or have a fast heartbeat. It is important to never self diagnose. Too much iron is toxic and should not be taken unless recommended by a medical professional.
.
. 
Female athletes are at risk of iron deficiency anaemia due to menstruation and high exercise output. Make sure if you are showing any of the symptoms to get it checked out by a doctor and never self diagnose.

Curried Cous Cous 💋
.
.
I'm a big fan of variety but a hectic schedule means it's often pretty hard to plan and make all the food I'd like to make 🙈 I'm a fan of making my own food and try to avoid convenience options as best as possible, but its sometimes unavoidable 🤷‍♀️
.
.
Cous cous is cheap and one of the quickest grains to make and can be super tasty if made well. Cous cous is lower in calories than most grains. But also lower in fibre. I have added chickpeas to the cous cous which lowers it's overall GI and increases it's fibre content 👌 I've also added vegetables, well because, health ❤️🙏
.
.
Ingredients:
- 200g Cous cous
- Curry powder
- Vegetable stock
- Paprika
- Chilli Powder
- Garlic
- Peppers
- Onions
-Chickpeas

Make up the cous cous with water (as instructed on pack). Add all spices. Wait 5 mins and add vegetables and chickpeas. *Mixture shouldn't be soggy

Enjoy 👌

#healthyalternatives #healthyliving #healthylifestyle #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitliving #fitlifestyle #fitfam #irishfitfam

Is Sleep really that important?
You’ve heard people say it’s important. That you need 8-10 hours per night. That without it you can’t function. But is there any real evidence to support everyone’s advice.
HELL YES!!!!
1.	Performance:
We’ve all heard, ‘Performance will suffer’. Recent studies have suggested that poor sleep is related to slower reaction times, compromised physical performance, increased risk of illness and injury, lower mood and decreased ability to learn and remember new skills. Poor sleep has been reported in elite athletes in numerous sports such as swimming, rugby, cricket, ice hockey and track and field. This is thought to be related to training times, competition stress/anxiety, muscle soreness, caffeine use, technology and travel. We found almost half (47.8 per cent) of GAA players monitored in a current study were poor sleepers, and those who were poor sleepers had significantly lower general health, increased stress and lower mood. 
Recent studies have found that: In a study of sleep interventions on athletes, sleep extension proved most beneficial to athletes. (1) Bonnar et al 2018. Another study claimed that increased sleep time improved sustained contraction time to exhaustions (2) Arnal et al. Meanwhile,  Inadequate sleep impairs maximal muscle strength in compound movements when performed without specific interventions designed to increase motivation. (3) Knowles et al

2.	Weight management
Short sleep duration and other aspects of poor sleep habits are growing in prevalence in modern society in both children and adults. A growing literature has established that short sleep duration and other dimensions of poor sleep are associated with obesity and appear to predict obesity risk and rate of weight gain longitudinally. Small experimental studies suggest poor sleep may impact dietary intake particularly hedonic eating. (4)  Ogilvie et al

3.	General Health 
A recent study showed that insufficient sleep and sleep disorders are highly prevalent and are associated with significant morbidity and mortality. Primary outcomes of insufficient sleep and/or sleep disorders are weight gain and obesity. Continued in comments

Do you really want to be lean? 🤔
.
.
Body Fat Percentage Norms
>32% Overweight/Obese
25-31% Normal
21-24% Fit
13-20% Athlete
10-12% Essential
.
. 
So apart from those genetically gifted people, being lean/athletic and remaining lean requires effort. Effort that a lot of people aren't willing to give. Time people aren't willing to put into it. And sacrifices people aren't willing to give up 🙈 I see it all the time. People with unrealistic goals. 😬
.
.
I (am not this lean right now) and a lot of GAA players are lean year round. Why?
Training 5-6 times a week, healthy eating to fuel our bodies and adequate recovery. We also have to give up on a lot of social occasions and probably drink much less than peers. It's a consistent process and has been for years.
.
.
But what about when people become too obsessed with body fat?
😬😬😬
- If your body fat is > 32% for a female, it is optimal for overall health to try and reduce this. But if your body fat is at 20% unless you are competing or need to make weight for sport, you don't need to be actively seeking to reduce this.
- Remember, females need more essential fat than men at about 12%. This is for our overall reproductive health. With low body fat, there is an increased risk in amenorrhoea (loss of period). This is due to the pituitary gland reducing production of hormones. This can have long term implications and can result in potential loss of reproductive function
- Other problems associated with a very low body fat can include: decreased bone mass density, problems with your heart, shrinkage of your organs, loss of muscle tissue, stomach problems and nervous system damage.
.
.
Please think of the long term implications of actively seeking a very low body fat. It may not affect you now if you are young, but down the road the health implications are daunting. Stop trying to look like people on Instagram (they don't even look like that) 😒😒😒 #lowbodyfat #lean #isitworthit #health #healthimplications #healthylifestyle #healthy #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitliving #fitlife #fitfam #irishfitfam

caption:
How do you eat healthy when you are 'on the go' and always busy? 🤔
.
.
So firstly, this is a cop out for a lot of people. Some people genuinely don't know what busy means and they use this as an excuse 😏😏😏 I've seen it all. I've had people tell me they can't eat well because they are 'too busy'. Why I asked? I work 10-5 and don't get a break. OK so what about the hours before 10 and after 5 🤔
I have seen the other end of the scale. I work with a lot of nurses who MAKE time. Even after their 12 hour night shifts. Even with children and a husband. So a lot of the time thís IS a choice. Personally, I have to prepare food and training gear up to 3 days in advance due to long days. .
.
But I have met others who it genuinely isn't. And eating on the road is the only option. If that is the case can you eat healthy?
✔️ Of course. The range of food choices has become so much better. There are healthy options available most places if you are looking for them.
👉 A lot of salad bowls are available in fridges. Greek yogurt is a great go to snack. Little pots of berries are often found along side them
👉 Fruit is never far away in most shops
👉 If you want something warm why not get soup and add chicken to it?
👉 Pre packaged foods like rice and lentils are always available if you have a microwave at work
👉 You can even get healthier options in fast food outlets. Wraps and Healthy Ciabattas are now available in most of them.
.
.
❌ You don't need to go for that carvery dinner every day. That is a choice.
❌ You can choose a healthier option in the deli, you just choose not to
❌ Being busy is NO excuse to have curry chips for lunch
.
.
#healthyalternatives #healthylifestyle #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitliving #fitlife #fitlifestyle #fitfam #irishfitfam

Why should women resistance train? 🤔
.
.
I asked this question a few weeks back and got a great response so I said I'd do a little post on it. So while yes I agree women can do anything men can do, that's not why I would be recommending to do it (a lot of your responses) 😂😂
.
.
Health benefits to resistance training
☑️ Increases bone density and strengthens joints - This is of particular importance as we get older. There is no age limit on resistance training. We should start young and continue it regularly throughout our lives ☑️ Increases lean muscle mass - Optimal body composition. Studies suggest that a combination of resistance and cardiovascular training is more beneficial for weight loss than either in isolation
.
.
Other benefits to resistance training
✔️ You get stronger 💪
✔️ Boosts body confidence 👙
✔️ Reduce body fat mass and increase muscle mass = Shape the body you want
.
.
Play Sport?
▶️ Stronger on the pitch
▶️ Reduce risk of injuries
▶️ Can improve endurance
.
.
If you're still questioning why you should be doing it? Questions below 👇👇👇 #resistancetraining #strongwomen #fitliving #fitlifestyle
#strengthtraining #sport #fitfam #irishfitfam

Listen up, this one is important. You don't want to fall down on this one 😜🤣 (I craic myself up😆🙈)
.
.
But honestly, it's the peak of championship, priority to every sports person out there should be performance 💪💪💪 If your goal is aesthetics, you're in sport for the WRONG reason 🙈🤔
.
.
So what does that all mean?
- Firstly, you need to be eating to fuel your performance. Large calorie deficits should be a thing of pre season, not mid season. (Now a slight calorie deficit may be OK, but I still would not be recommending it for clients). Food is so important. Stocking up on carbs, an abundance of protein and lots of healthy fats 👌 If you are lean this time of year, it should be as a result of lots of training, not lots of dieting.  I personally am sitting at about 22% Body Fat. That's probably more than my regular BF % but I am eating in maintenance and maybe even a little bit of a surplus just to be sure I am getting enough fuel 👌 This weekend I had 2 games. It's not the first time and it won't be the last. I've trained 6 times this week and it's so important to get the most out of your body on game day 👌 - Secondly, it goes back to my burnout post. You need to fuel ✔️ But you seriously need to recover. I'm starting to take up a pool session a week to aid with my recovery. I am in an ice bath almost every day and I see a chiropractor every  4-6 weeks. Now is not the time of year to be hitting PBs in the gym 😬 The gym shouldnt get shoved out the window but maintenance should be all you should be looking for right now 👍
.
.
Remember, performance is priority. Do everything you can to improve and progress that. Eat well and recover right 👌 That extra few pounds could be the difference between a good game and a great game 😜💪 #health #aesthetics #performance #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitliving #fitlife #fitfam #irishfitfam

Exercise on your period😒😒😒
.
. 
People still seem to be afraid to talk about this topic 🙈 It's such a natural thing which all us ladies have to deal with so I'm so glad someone asked me to talk on this topic 😊
.
.
Let's be honest none of us WANT to do it, especially if you are crippled with period pains 😩 And there's a lot of non sense out there telling us we 'shouldn't' do this that and the other 🤔 So what is the truth?
.
.
Well firstly like with most things I talk about it is very individual dependent. If you have a low iron count or anaemia, this time of month is very difficult to exercise. You are an exception to the norm. But for most of us there's no need to cut out exercise. Sometimes we MAY just need to cut down especially if you have a heavy flow and are losing a lot of blood 😔
.
.
Why should we exercise during our period?
✔️ Decreases PMS symptoms
✔️ Endorphins - our feel good factor
✔️ Reduces period pains
✔️ Enhances your mood 😊
.
.
What type of exercise should we do?
-As I said before, most of the time we can just keep up with our normal exercise routine but yoga and pilates can be quite beneficial.
- Did you know that during your period you're stronger? So low rep strength training can be benificial 💪
.
.
Hope this helps 💪💪💪 #periods #femaletraining #trainingonyourperiod #fitliving #fitlifestyle #fitlife #fitfam #irishfitfam

caption:
Do you suffer from burnout? 🚫🚫🚫
.
.
Every year around this time of year, someone on your team is likely to suffer from burnout 😔 A recent survey done with intercounty minors showed that 62% of underage players played while carrying injuries and 42% experienced chronic fatigue 😳
.
.
The GAA calendar year is long. For some of us it doesn't stop. You need to know how to adapt and tailor training to different cycles during the year. If you're lucky enough to have a great coach, they will be able to do this for you, if not, you need to seek help. The same level of training cannot be continued year long. Everybody needs periods of Deload especially athletes 👌
.
.
I train year long. I don't take long breaks. And I know my body craves and needs it. I try to Deload but I'm not the best at listening to my own advice. Until this year 💡 Other people would think I'm mad taking a rest period before championship starts but thats exactly what my body needed ❤️ I normally train 5/6 times a week but with reducing my training by 1 or 2 days a week for June, my body thanked me and my energy levels are exactly where they need to be this time of year 😊 I have also had to step away from my beloved Crossfit the weeks of championship games 😭 As football is priority at the moment. But for once I'm listening to my body and performance is the main goal 👌 Maybe you should too? 👂👂👂 #champo #championship #burnout #praticewhatyoupreach #fitliving #fitlife #fitlifestyle #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitfam #irishfitfam

caption:
Patience and Consistency 🙏🙏🙏
.
.
If you are missing either of these traits your fitness journey is gonna be a difficult one 😢
.
.
Tried every diet going? Seeing nó results? Tried spinning? Didn't see results? Tried weightlifting? Didn't see results? Tried 10,000 steps a day? Didn't see results? Tried eating less and moving more? Still no results?
.
.
Now did you try any of these for more than a few weeks 🤔 Because that's what it takes. It takes time. It takes effort. It won't happen in a few weeks. It might even take a few years 🤷‍♀️ But you have to stick at it. And not just for how you look. But for how you feel. ❤️ For your health, your wellbeing, your life 👆👆👆
.
.
And it's a HECK of a lot easier if you'd just start enjoying the process 🌠🌠🌠 #fitness #fitliving #happiness #health #healthylifestyle #healthy #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitgirls #fitfam #irishfitfam

Do We Need Breakfast?
.
. 
Well firstly it’s a myth that anyone ‘needs’ breakfast. 
But we were always told that breakfast is the most important meal of the day?
If you questioned why. You were probably told because your metabolism starts when you eat breakfast. If you have breakfast, your metabolism starts earlier. And probably that you burn more calories if you eat breakfast or ‘you’ll lose weight’ eating breakfast. Well according to Betts et al 2014 [1] Daily Breakfast consumption has no effect on resting metabolism. For those of you who hate breakfast or those of you who like to fast, there is hope 😁 Does that mean don’t eat breakfast? Absolutely not. I’m a regular breakfast eater. I could not go without it. But I deal with clients daily who ‘Don’t have time’ or ‘can’t stomach it’ so I won’t force them to consume it. The answer really is do you want breakfast, if no, don’t eat it, if yes, enjoy 😊  You may have also been told the more meals you have in a day equates to burning more calories and boosts your metabolism more. 
This is also a myth. The thermic effect of food is the same if you have 6 meals or 2 meals. Sometimes having small frequent meals can actually prove a hindrance as you may overconsume on calories. Dashti et al. 2017 [2]. Your metabolism or metabolic rate is highly influenced by your overall calorie consumption, your food choices, your NEAT and your purposeful exercise. It is overall daily calorie intake that is what matters, not necessarily how you distribute it. Unless in certain circumstances like athletic performance or muscle retention, where it may be important. 
So finally, it really comes down to personal preference. Do what suits you and your lifestyle. Remember, when it comes to metabolic rate, overall calories are important. What is not important is meal timing or meal frequency. 😊

1.	 The causal role of breakfast in energy balance and health: a randomized controlled trial in lean adults. Betts et al. 
Am J Clin Nutr. 2014 
2.	Recommending Small, Frequent Meals in the Clinical Care of Adults: A Review of the Evidence and Important Considerations. Dashti et al
Nutr Clin Pract 2017

caption:
Ever felt peer pressure to eat something you didn't want to 🙋‍♀️🙋‍♀️🙋‍♀️
.
.
This is one that gets on my wick 🙈
Firstly, I don't want the f*#cking donut Susan, it's none of your business as to why. I just don't feel I need to eat a sugar and fat laden food at 10am that is going to make my stomach churn. There is absolutely NOTHING wrong with eating the donut, unless you are guilted into it. Everyone has their own goals, and if you don't to eat/do something you're under no obligation to explain yourself. If people don't respect your decision well they can go 🖕 Same goes for drinking. If you aren't drinking you're either pregnant or on antibiotics, people can't seem to accept 'I'm just not drinking as an excuse' 🙈 Worry more about yourself, and not what others are doing 👌
.
.
Secondly, yes you are human. Even as a nutritionist I enjoy crisps with my friends or I might opt for a dessert. And when I'm on holiday 😂 I go all out 😜Just because I eat very healthy majority of the time doesn't mean I don't enjoy normal meals out and a few drinks 😁 So please don't say 'Omg I didn't think you'd eat that😒'.
.
.
Choosing health is a choice made by a lot of people. Sometimes it's a hard decision and is forced upon them by health issues or illness. Some people struggle with it, others enjoy it. Whether it's easy or difficult, nobodies motives should be questioned. 😏 I am so lucky I have such a supportive bunch of friends and family, who know my tupperware comes with me everywhere (apart from to the chipper at 3am after Rockfords😂) .
.
'You do you' ❤️ #healthyalternatives #healthylifestyle #fitlifestyle #fitliving #fitgirls #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitfam #irishfitfam

caption:
Just to clarify...
.
.
✔️Its OK to go on a holiday.
✔️It's OK to take a little break(physically and mentally)
Even if it is in the middle of championship 🏐🏐🏐
.
.
I feel like sometimes people forget this is a hobby. You're not paid. You don't get that much recognition. And yet you're expected to act like an elite athlete.
.
.
For me:
Holidays are a necessity. I work my normal 40 hours. I have my online clients which probably bring my working week up to 60 hours. I drive 1.5-3hrs daily. I rise at 5am at least 3 times a week and am in bed every night at 11 because of either work or training. I do something every weekend because I like to keep busy. And that's before training. I train 4 times a week with football and 1/2 of my own sessions. ✔️That's who I am and I like being super busy.
.
. 
Holidays give me time to relax and unwind and without them I would never do that.
I used to be that person who sacrificed everything to play football. I still sacrifice a lot, you have to. But I was sacrificing my happiness and probably a little bit of my health.
.
.
I structure it that I don't miss any games and I always feel so mentally refreshed coming back onto the pitch so I think it's a win win 😁 I know a lot of coaches may not like this post but remember it's you as the player who is the most important and valuable asset to a team. 👌
.
.
Now to focus on retaining a Connacht title 💯💯💯 #holidays #itsoktohavealife #sacrifices #commitment #fitliving #gaagirls #gaelicgirls #fitness #fitlifestyle #fitlife #fitfam #irishfitfam

Fat gets a bad rep. Sure it is 9Kcal per gram but it is an essential part of a balanced fat. Fats provide us with energy, makes up our cell membranes as well as our brain and nervous system. Fats are necessary to transport vitamins A,D,E and K and make and balance certain hormones. Fat can be found in 2 forms:
Saturated – mainly found in animal products like meat, dairy, eggs, coconut
Unsaturated – found in marine sources like fish oils, as well as nuts, seeds and vegetable oils
.
. 
For years saturated fat was thought to be associated with higher risk of Cardiovascular Disease and so it was deemed as ‘unhealthy’ or ‘bad for you’. The problem with saturated fat was not the actual fat itself but rather the increased consumption of processed food or the large quantities of saturated fat products. Saturated fat helps increase the cholesterol production in the body which is an essential part of metabolism and in the production of steroid hormones. So saturated fat should feature in our diet, just maybe don’t latter every meal in butter.
.
. 
Unsaturated fats are made up of mono and polyunsaturated fats.  These contain our omega 3 and omega 6 fatty acids. Omega 3 fatty acids open our airways and blood vessels. They reduce our blood lipids and cholesterol and lower inflammation and pain. Omega 6 fatty acids do the opposite. Both are needed in the body, without both we wouldn’t heal or recover from exercise. The problem with Western diets is that we don’t have the proper ratios. We are at about 10:1 where we should be at 2:1 (omega 6/omega 3).
.
. 
Low fat diets were a fad a few years ago. While people reduced calories, they increased their intake of processed foods. Diets lacked fats and fat soluble vitamins so instead of being healthier people were losing weight but were not healthier.
.
. 
Fats are an essential part of any healthy diet. Be aware that they are very calorie dense so be sure not to overconsume and don’t opt for processed versions. Enjoy them as part of a balanced lifestyle.

caption:
Once upon a time I was obsessed with having abs and glutes. I was so obsessed I would take daily photos of myself. Hoping and praying I'd look different 🙏 I would eat in a bid for those abs. I ate really clean and I'd end up on a chocolate binge at Weekends and I was so upset with not having the body I always wanted😭😭
.
.
When my Dad died, my whole outlook on life changed. Health became a priority to me and abs no longer seemed so important. As soon as I started caring more about my health, I started to enjoy my training a lot more 😍 I was still eating very well but I wasn't obsessing about 'bad food'.
.
.
Fast forward 3 years later and I am so incredibly proud of my body. Not for what it looks like but for what it can do ❤️ And the irony of it is, I'm probably in the best shape of my life as result.
.
.
Life is so much more important than micro managing every morsel of food you eat and punishing yourself for eating 'bad food'.
.
.
'You are your own most important asset, start treating yourself like you are'

After Spice Girls at the Weekend and one too many West Coast Coolers I just wanted to show you a little swap I made awhile back 👌👌 Now, before I start, neither drink is a 'healthy' option (you'd be suprised how often I hear that).

.
While a pink gin and slimline tonic comes in at about 70 calories, it's convenient can option is a very different kettle of fish 🙊 Again, alcohol is empty calories but if you are drinking these cans thinking you're going for the 'good option', 5 of these cans will set you back almost 1000 Calories (and let's be honest they are easy to drink 😜).

caption:
How to get a bikini body.
Step 1. Put on a bikini. 👙
.
. 
While I wish it were that simple for everyone to be that confident. Not everyone is. Truth is every single woman out there has insecurities 😭 Myself included. I'd be pretty comfortable in a bikini year round but there are tips I recommend to make you feel good whilst on holidays ☀️
.
.
Like most I enjoy myself on holidays. I drink, I eat rich food and I exercise less. All these differences to my lifestyle and add in the fact that I have a sensitive stomach can cause a lot of bloating and water retention. 🐋 I try to keep this at bay as best as possible so I feel confident in my bikini 👌
.
. 
1. Drink as much water as possible. Alcohol plus salty food can equal a lot of fluid retention so it's important to get guzzling that water. Not to mention the other side effects of dehydration like headaches and vomiting. Nobody wants that on holidays. I also bring electrolytes and dandelion Root with me.
.
.
2. Do a little exercise. While I take a break from my heavy 5-6 day routine I like to get a session in every 2-3 days. If you're not interested in the gym when away nó problem. Why not go for a run or cycle? And walk EVERYWHERE 👌
.
.
3. Don't take the piss. If you want to eat like an absolute fool, do, but don't complain about the stomach cramps or diarrhoea. 🤷‍♀️ If I'm going to Indulge in a heavy meal for dinner, I'll have a decent breakfast or vice versa. Keep protein with every meal and reduce snacking if it's leading to a massive consumption in calories. .
.
4. Don't drink all your calories. Cocktails are great 🍹 But don't forget they contain calories too, so does the 3 fantas a day and your baileys coffee after dinner 🙊 Again, I suffer if I eat a lot of sugar so I know not to over consume on these, but some of you might need some reminding 🤣😵
.
.
It's not all doom and gloom. You won't ruin all your progress if you do decide to go all out. I just know some of you suffer with the same symptoms as me and hopefully this might help you 😊
.
.
Enjoy holidays ☀️ #holidaytips, #healthylifestyle #healthyliving #fitlife #fitlifestyle #bikinibody #confidence #fitfam #irishfitfam

I am not an s&c coach so I won't be giving advice on the different phases and cycles you should have in the gym. Although I have a very good idea it's not my area of expertise so I'll leave that to the experts 👌👌👌
.
.
What I do know?
- Resistance training is essential to reduce injury risk. Doing it pre season is not enough. You need to dedicate at least one day a week to it. The game speed and strength has dramatically increased. So too has the injury count. We need to keep on top of our games.
.
.
But what if I'm sore for training/match?
- Doms predominantly occur from:
1. A break from training and ré introduction of weights. Best way to avoid this, don't take a week off and definitely don't take more than that 😕
2. A new stimulus - maybe a new programme with the introduction of new exercises. Don't start this the day before a game 😑
3. Under recovery - Not getting in sufficient food and water post exercise
.
.
What should I be doing then?
Again, this won't be too highly detailed. Not my area of expertise 👆
- Volume shouldn't be crazy high - Rep ranges should probably be lower with higher weights. There's no need for a 12 exercise, hypertrophic leg day in the middle of championship 😩😩
- Exercises that transfer over onto the pitch - Strength, Power and plyomteric exercises. NOT bicep curls 😂💪 LADS that one is aimed at ye 🤦‍♀️🤦‍♀️🤦‍♀️
- If you're recovering from an injury, you need to keep up with individual rehab as well as what everyone else is doing 👌

Hope thís helps. I get ALOT of questions regarding this one, but I don't want to delve into territory that is not mine, I'll leave that to the experts 👍

#gymwork #gaa #gaagirls #fitliving #fitlife #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitfam #irishfitfam

If I could give my younger self advice (listen up teens👂)
.
.
👉 Travel - whatever opportunity you get do it. J1, family holiday, interailing, city breaks. Just GO!!!!! Single best decision I've ever made was to go to Thailand with my friends. I have never looked back since. And the bucket list is slowly filling ✔️✔️✔️
👉 Stop exercising for weight loss, start exercising for health. Your WHOLE outlook changes and my God it is AMAZING what our bodies can do ❤️ And for the love of God find something you enjoy 😢 If you hate spinning, stop spinning. If you'd rather yoga to the gym, that's fine. If dancing is your thing, dance the night away 💃🕺
👉 Stop stressing. WE ARE IN CONTROL!!!!! I wish I learned this one sooner. Stress is still something I struggle with but I'm getting better 👌😉 Life is so much brighter without the weight of the world on your shoulders 😭 I heard yesterday that 6 out of 10 Leaving certs have had a physical or mental ailment from the stress of the Leaving Cert 😮 Take it from someone who's hair started falling out during the L.C. It's not worth it 😑😑
👉 Drink less. Alcohol in my teens, early twenties was excessive, there is no 2 ways about it. To a point of almost a problem. I still drink. I'm still a light weight 😂🙊 But it's no longer a problem. I know I might sound like an old Granny but if you become a terrible person when you are drinking, is it really worth it? 🤔
👉 Eat more. Food is fuel. Food is healthy. It breaks my heart to hear of younger girls depriving themselves😭 Eating disorders, poor relationships with themselves and excessive exercise are all on the increase. Stop trying to look like girls on Instagram, the girls themselves don't even look like that 😭
.
.
If this helped one person today, my day would be made ❤️
.
.
P. S yes that is an espresso martini in my hand 😂

caption:
Sweet potato versus white potato🥔🍠
.
. 
The humble spud got a very bad rep in the last couple of years and the reign of the sweet potato took over. All potato recipes were substituted with sweet potato and sweet potato fries were on every menu. What is the difference between the two tubers?
.
. 
When you compare 100g of each baked, there is very little difference calorie wise. Carbohydrate and fibre wise they are practically identical. The main nutritional difference would be the significantly higher vitamin A content in Sweet potato and the white potato contains more potassium. Both have a High GI when cooked. .
. 
So, if you are thinking you’re ‘healthier’ eating Sweet potato, remember there is place for both types of potato in your diet and both should be enjoyed as part of a balanced diet 😊

#sweetpotato #whitepotato
#enjoyboth #comparisons #healthyalternatives #healthylifestyle #fitliving #fitlifestyle #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitfam #irishfitfam

I put up a poll yesterday to see are people being led by marketing. While I was delighted to see most people don't think dairy free, gluten free or vegan = healthy. Over 40 of you answered yes. 🤔
.
.
Companies have become really smart recently with their marketing strategies and are constantly using buzz words like gluten free or high protein. These buzz words do not automatically make a food healthy. The only person that NEEDS to eat gluten free is a coeliac. Now that being said a gluten free diet can simply be an elimination of processed wheat, barley, and rye based products. But there is no need to opt for gluten free products because you think they are healthier. They are often heavily processed and again are not necessary unless you are coeliac. Same goes for dairy free 🙄 As for Vegan, this is a new buzzword. Plant based should be a large part of every diet for all the micronutrients, water and phytonutrients it gives us 😍 But getting a 'vegan sausage roll' will not make you a health queen 😂 Remember, if weight loss is a goal, calories are king. So if you are choosing between a raw cacao, nut butter, hazelnut infused brownie (400 cals) and an Eton mess (200cals), the Eton mess is probably the better option for your dietary goals. It may not be refined Sugar free but it's lower in calories (not based on actual calories). Finally, my favourite, high protein label. Everything has protein in it now: bars, bread, even water 😂
.
.
Just keep it simple. Plant based fruit and vegetables with each meal and snack. If you eat meat, buy from a butchers or reliable source. Natural protein sources include a lot of dairy based products, meat, fish, eggs, and legumes. Natural wholegrains, and tubers for our carbohydrate sources. Natural oils rather than man-made products. It's not rocket science. Don't give into marketing strategies, a lot of the time it's 🐃💩 #labelling #marketing #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #eatforgoals #fitliving #fitlifestyle #fitfam #irishfitfam

caption:
What is Fibre and why is it important? 🤔 - Fibre comes in 2 different forms:soluble and insoluble. We can't digest these, but they have very important roles in the body especially within our gut.
.
.
Soluble fibre is found in fruit, oats, dried beans and peas, nuts, barley and chia.
.
.
Insoluble fibre is found vegetables, fruit and vegetable skins, seeds and nuts
.
.
☑️Fibre helps us feel fuller for longer
☑️Lowers our risk of Colon cancer
☑️ Speeds up digestion through our GI tract
☑️ Bulks up our stools
☑️ Lowers our blood lipids and Cholesterol
☑️Boost overall gut health

We need approximately 25-35g per day. In Ireland, we tend to not eat enough fibre and thus we can have issues with our gut health. Too much can cause digestive stress so it's important to get just the right amount👌

#fibre #itsimportant #healthyalternatives
#healthylifestyle #fitliving #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitlife #fitfam #irishfitfam

While I love it, and I mostly have positive things to say about it. Never EVER forget it is only a hobby. I give out about it a lot 😂 But I still enjoy it. These sacrifices will include social occasions. Again, expect that. If it starts affecting other elements of your life, your job, relationships or your health, that's where you draw a line. Coming back to the fact that any sport is a hobby. Gaa is not paid, and the sacrifices do mimic a professional sport. So enjoy the sport. Remember that's why you are doing it. 🤔 Don't let it dictate your life. And if you feel it is, there are loads of other hobbies out there 👌😉 #gaagirls #gaelicgirls #fitliving #fitlifestyle #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitfam #irishfitfam

caption:
What are the components to fitness and how do I get fitter? This can be a very scientific topic so I'm going to put it in as simple terms as possible 👌
.
.
Firstly, you need to push outside a comfort zone or a tolerance limit. Most people will stay in that. And while staying in that zone will keep you at the same fitness levels, its pushing outside it that will ultimately improve your fitness. Let's be brutally honest, we've all seen it, the fittest players getting fitter while the unfit players pull out of sessions. This may not actually be their fault either. With team sports, there are all fitness levels. While you try to push the fittest on the team, sometimes it's too much on the unfit players which leads to dropout. If playing team sports, runs/sprints should be staggered (fitter players have more to do). Bench players should also have extra to do so they don't fall behind starting players. There is no one size fits all and that's hard to do with team sports. (This is purely opinion)
.
.
You need to train in the right energy systems. You don't see a Sprinter constantly doing 5ks (which is an aerobic system), no you see them work in an anaerobic system. If they are sprinting, they are working their creatine phosphate system, if they are in the gym, they are using the same energy system. If you are a field sport player, you need a bit of both. You need to be able to access your anaerobic system for short sprints and your aerobic system for recovery. That's why your trainer should have you doing both fast, speed work and endurance work. If you are poor in either of those areas, you need to work on them 😁
.
.
Hydration and Nutrition. Never ever underestimate these powerful tools. We only train about 10% of our time. The other 90% is sleep, recovery and nutrition. What you put into your body has a huge impact on your fitness levels. I talked about food and the importance of it not just for fuel but for other essential bodily functions 👌
.
.
Recovery. In the form of food, hydration, sleep, and physical rest. Our bodies are smart. If you Constantly 'grinding', our bodies don't have time to adapt. They are in overdrive.
Continued in comments

caption:
People over complicate everything 🙀🙀
.
.
Nutrition is relatively simple. Not necessarily easy, but simple. Exercise is the same. Eat better, move more 😍
.
.
I have people coming to me, sprinting before they have even learned to walk. Yes, I've heard it all. I've had overweight/obese people give out to me about my food choices as they are not organic or may be genetically modified🤔 I've had people who lived on takeaways all of a sudden are now vegan. And don't even get me started on going gluten and lactose free 😫🙊 Guys, get your house in order. If you are over weight none of these extremes are necessary. If you cut back a little on treats, controlled portion size and ate more vegetables you could probably sort all your problems out. It may be a slower process but it's a consistent one. I'm not trying to be harsh. I'm actually trying to be nice and say it's more simple than you are making it 😫
.
.
As for exercise. Going from nothing to something is always a benefit. But make sure it's not just purposeful exercise. Increasing your steps daily will have a huge benefit on your Basal Metabolic rate. And as for the best exercise, that is the one you enjoy the most and can sustain. I know people that exercise that absolutely hate it and do it for the sake of it 😭 Exercise should be something you enjoy, not endure, so find one you like❤️. I would recommend some form of resistance training on top of it, as it's hugely beneficial for bone, ligament and tendon health as well as maintaining lean muscle mass.
.
.
So stop over complicating healthy eating and exercise. You don't need to be a gluten and lactose free vegan to be healthy, nor do you need to be a crossfit athlete. Get moving daily, stop treating yourself so often (you don't need it), reduce your portion size and increase your vegetable consumption. Thats a great start right there 👆😁 #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #eatwell #stopovercomplicatingthings #healthylifestyle #fitlifestyle #fitliving #fitfam #irishfitfam

caption:
As I wake up this morning barely able to move I'm thinking back on the great day we had @midlandsthrowdown yesterday 😁😁😁 I am so proud of @david.hoare93 and the members from @fullbodyworkhouse who came and competed. They all did absolutely incredible 🎉🎉🎉 Especially my partner in crime @keelafarnon 💪💪💪 To think this girl is only 18 still mesmerises me 😲 .
.
Finally, I'm so proud of myself 😊 Yep I said it. I did my first fitness competition in October last year without training so I'm relatively new to this but I absolutely love it. caption:
I'm not a physio and I won't be giving you a big list of exercises to do for ACL rehab. Also, every injury is so different and every individual is so specialised and specific I won't be giving a one size fits all approach, because there isn't one 🤔🤔🤔
.
.
What I will say is 2 things:
👉 Firstly, don't underestimate the influence of nutrition on the healing process. What you put in your body is as important as your rehab exercises. Never forget that. 👆👆👆
.
.
👉 Secondly, if and hopefully when you get back on the pitch. Just because you are back from injury does not mean you are healed. If you don't keep on top of your strength and rehab work, your chances of re injury is increasingly higher. Keep on top of your strength work. Not just your quads (most of us footballers are quad dominant which isn't helped by the fact that when we do leg work it's mostly quad dominant work) but hamstrings and glutes need attention. Glute exercises include: Hip Trusters, Hip Bridges and Band Work. Hamstrings need to do 2 things: Knee Flexion (exercises like leg curls, Nordics) and Hip Extension (RDL).
.
.
From my experience, staying on top of my nutrition and strength work has hugely benefited me since I had ACL reconstruction 4.5 years ago 💪💪💪 #consistency #rehab #strengthtraining #gaagirls #gaelicgirls #fitlifestyle #fitliving #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitfam #irishfitfam

One of the most common questions I get asked is about a pre match meal. Well let me tell you, pre Match fuel begins long before the pre match meal. 😃
.
.
As discussed in previous posts, carbohydrates are the main fuel source involved in GAA. We can store 80-100g in our liver and 300-600g in our muscles as glycogen. But as glucose is constantly being used as a fuel source it is constantly depleting therefore we need to top it up regularly.
.
.
Pre Match nutriton begins the day before a game. So if you play Sunday at 2pm. You should be topping glycogen stores from 2pm Saturday. I recommend a carbohydrate source with each meal like Cous cous for lunch, potatoes for dinner and oats for breakfast the following morning. Closer to game time, fruit is a great source of cárbohydrate. Protein is also essential. As athletes we are constantly in recovery mode for our next session so protein needs to be a part of our pre Match routine. Although it won't be used as fuel it is an important element for muscle repair etc.
.
.
Some don'ts the day of a game
❌❌❌ ❎ High fat foods are harder to break down in the body and may cause gastrointestinal upset so best to avoid large quantities of fat. Save them for afterwards when we need to reduce inflammation
❎ High fibre foods can also cause gastrointestinal issues and while fibre is a vital part of a healthy diet, its best to avoid large quantities before games
❎ Strong flavoured foods .
.
Some dos
✔️✔️✔️
☑️ Nutrient dense foods with a cárbohydrate and protein element
👉Oats with whey protein, Eggs and Toast, fruit salad with Greek Yogurt, Chicken and pasta, fish and potatoes
☑️ Don't forget about water. Hydration is a key pre Match ritual

Hope this helps 😃 Never change a routine the day of a game. Slowly make changes in the days leading up to a game 👌

#eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitlife #prematch #nutrition #fitliving #fitfam #irishfitfam

Listen up, this one is an important one.👂
.
.
Yes macros are important. Carbohydrate is the main source of energy for most sports. Protein is essential for repair and recovery. Fats are anti inflammatory and necessary for fat soluble vitamin transport. Yes your macronutrients which convert into energy are fuel for the body.
.
.
But what about micronutrients, phytonutrients and zoo chemicals. These don't directly fuel us but they are also vital to the functioning of the human body. They are responsible for vital internal functions and without them our bodies would not be able to asorb nutrients or convert them to energy. They are vital for gut health, immunity, nervous system functioning, nutrient absorbtion, digestion... The list goes on. 📃 As humans, our bodies don't just do one thing at a time (even if we think we are). Just to be alive, all our systems are working internally. Imagine adding eating and drinking to that. Now let's add a job. Let's add a family. Let's add exercise. Our bodies are constantly working, there is no off switch 📴 Sometimes are bodies are under serious strain. If we are not getting the vital nutrients we need to keep up with this pressure, major problems can occur within the body. 😞
.
.
I don't give opinions on this very often but I'm going to for this one. If you are constantly worrying/counting macros and not focusing on food quality that's fine, you'll get the fuel you need for your body. But overall, internally, you are not focusing on the other functions in your body. Your body is more than just an engine that you need to fuel. It's complex and deserves to be treated like your most important possession. Because really, that's what it is 🤔🤔🤔 #foodisnorethanfuel #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitlife #fitlifestyle #fitliving #healthylifestyle #fitfam #irishfitfam

Let's just get one thing straight the optimal body composition for EVERYONE is a high lean muscle mass and a lower body fat mass. That includes having strong bones, joints, ligaments and tendons. This is the composition our body thrives on and is most healthy in. That is the body composition everyone should be aiming for. 👌 Now, that doesn't mean you will get muscular or bulky 😂 I understand that my muscle mass is not for everyone but believe me, most of you will never have to worry about that 😂
.
.
How to gain muscle:
👉 First thing you need is a lot of patience. Especially if you want to gain muscle and remain relatively lean. The difference between these photos is 4 years and there's still not that much difference 😂
👉 You need food. Food is fuel. Generally, you need to be in a slight calorie surplus to gain muscle. Protein and carbs are your best friends ❤️
👉 Resistance training. From my experience, volume and time under tension are 2 of the main aids for gaining muscle. Rep ranges of about 8-12 are working in a hypertrophy range of building muscle. But it's good to mix strength, hypertrophy and endurance.
👉 Frequency. Don't expect results from training twice a week. It's not necessarily about training 2 hours a day every day but frequency is important. Train smarter not harder.
👉 Recovery. This relates to food, hydration, sleep and physical rest. Your body needs to repair itself to grow.

And enjoy the process 🎉🎉🎉 #muscle #girlswithmuscle #bodycomposition #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitliving #fitlifestyle #fitlife #fitfam #irishfitfam

caption:
This is one I get asked on a lot. So here is a very general guide.
.
.
Step 1: Weight in kg x (22-24)
- 22 Low Activity Level daily - 23 Medium Activity Level daily
- 24 High Activity Level daily
.
.
Step 2: Mutiply this number by training frequency level (1.2 - 2.0)
- 1.2 - Little to no training
- 1.4 - Training 1-3 times per week
- 1.6 - Training 3-5 times per week
- 1.8 - Training 6-7 times per week
- 2.0 - Training 6-7 times a week with highly active job or 2+ per day
.
.
Step 3: Adjust for goals
If maintenance is a goal. You have it. If weight loss is a goal minus the percentage body weight you want to lose. If weight gain is a goal add the percentage body weight you want to gain.
.
.
Example: 30 year old woman who works at a desk job wants to lose 6kg. She is currently 66kg and trains about 3 times a week.
66 x 22 = 1452

1452 x 1.4 = 2032

2032 x 90% (wants to loose 10% BW) = 1832 per day (you could go a little lower if you wanted to speed up weight loss, this number is for a slow, sustainable weight loss) .
.
I have no problem with my fitness pal but please stop getting your calorie and macro figures from it. It is not accurate or tailored to you 😑😑😑 It is a good tool to track foods but not to get calories and macros on 😒

#calories #caloriecounting #fitliving #fitlifestyle #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #foodisfuel #fitfam #irishfitfam

caption:
Are Macro and Micro Nutrients important for Athletes??? YES!!!!
.
.
Let's delve into what we need each nutrient for and requirement levels.
.
.
Protein 🥩🍳🥓
Every cell in your body needs protein. Protein is absolutely essential for athletes due to the amount of training they are doing. Protein turnover is very high so demands for protein are also very high. We need it for recovery and muscle repair. It is also very important in times of injury. I recommend 2g per Kg of Bodyweight.
Sources include: Meat, Fish, Eggs, Beans, Legumes. Eat protein at every meal.
.
.
Carbohydrates 🥔🥪🍚
Carbohydrate is the preferred fuel for GAA. It gives us energy in the form of glucose or stored glycogen. There are 2 types of carbohydrates:Complex carbohydrates and simple sugars. Complex carbohydrates are the ones we want most of in our diet. They not only provide fuel but also fibre which is essential for gut health. I recommend about 3g per Kg Bodyweight. This can increase days of games/trainings or day before to almost 6g per Kg Bodyweight. Sources include: Rice, Oats, Fruit, Potatoes, Sweet Potato.
.
.
Fats 🥑🌰🧀
Fats are often neglected and are a very important part of an athletes diet. Fats reduce inflammation (caused by exercise or injury), they are part of our cell membranes and they transport vitamins A, D, É & K. I recommend about 1-1.5g per Kg BW. This can increase or decrease based on carbohydrate consumption. Sources include: Avocado, nuts, seeds, dark chocolate, oily fish
.
.
Micronutrients 🍉🥦🥒
These are often overlooked. Although they are required in small quantities, lack of consumption can lead to serious deficiencies. Not only is immune function lowered increasing risk of catching colds and illnesses which can increase absenteeism from training. Cognitive function can be impaired (not ideal on a pitch). Micronutrient deficiencies in some cases can cause fatigue like a lack of Iron or B Group Vitamins. Water would also be considered a micronutrient
. .
 It is important to look at the big picture. It's not just macros that are important to athletes. We need micronutrients for our overall recovery and health 🏃‍♀️🏋️‍♀️

Let's talk Confidence🙊🙊🙊
.
.
People assume I've always been confident. This is so far from the case. Confidence is not something you are born with. It's something you choose to become, in my opinion 👌
.
.
I'll tell you my struggles with confidence we've all had them.
.
.
When I was a teenager I struggled with my appearance. I would wear make up every single day. I would never be seen without make up. I was so afraid what people would think of my bare face 😩 Would Boys still like me😩 I struggled with body image (as most teenagers do). I was tiny. But I always thought I could be thinner. My distorted image of exercise was for weight loss only. It just helped that I actually liked football. 😔
.
.
Football was my biggest confidence barrier. Because I was never skillful I never really believed in myself. I wasn't the player people 'talked about'. EVER. I made my club and school team. I was always on the bench for Roscommon so I did what I needed to. Then, my first year in college I was picked for the O Connor Cup squad. I was one of only 7 first years. But nerves crept in rather than confidence. I remember playing a 7s competition with some very big names from Dublin and Donegal and I just flopped. I had no confidence in my ability. I couldn't overcome the nerves. And I struggled with this for afew years in college.
.
.
When I came out of college. I questioned myself with my career. Am I good enough? Do I know enough? Do I practice what I preach? Do I look good enough" (for a personal trainer)?
.
.
Fast forward to getting older and wiser. And speaking to a lot of people along the way❤️ I'm make up free most days🤣 I'm still not skillful but I'm fairly confident in my footballing ability 👌 What I look like has no correlation to the trainer I am. Which is a good one. As a nutritionist, I base my beliefs and advice on science. I don't know everything. I'm constantly learning and I love it 😁 I'm not perfect but then again, perfect doesn't exist 👆👆👆 #fitlife #confidence #confident #fitness #fitlifestyle #fitliving #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitfam #irishfitfam

I have 2 regrets from the last 20 years of playing football. Not much over 2 decades. My first one was not doing a j1 because of football 🙊 My second was not playing my last ever O Connor Cup game with UCD because I was sick 😭 (which I was my whole final year 😩)
.
.
Because I never went away or went further than the Canaries I thought I had no interest in travelling. 3 years ago, My friends were travelling South East Asia and my Dad had just died when I decided I'd meet them in Thailand for a holiday. It absolutely blew me away. What had I been missing out on all this time. The scenery, the culture, the heat, the sun, the food, the buckets 🤣🤣🤣 The best day of my life to date was in Thailand. Since then, I've become a boring dry shite day to day. My weekends are always football based so I don't go out. I can't really go away. So I save up now, for holidays. Last year I was on 17 different flights. This year is a little more low key but I'm already making big plans for next year 😊
.
.
Everyone is different but for me holidays and travel are life. I need them. They relax me (and there's no other way of doing that 🤣). Any opportunity you get to go away, take it. ❤️ #travel #instatravel #bucketlist #travelmore #europe #asia #fitliving #fitfam #irishfitfam

Food. Nutrition. Weight Loss. Weight Gain. Performance. Sleep. The list goes on....
.
.
First thing is first, you need to figure out is your goal. If its weight loss. Calories are king. Not low cárb or high cárb or keto or Atkins. Calories. Being in a caloric deficit. Please don't use myfitnesspal calories as they cut you down to insanely low daily intake 😱 Which will have an impact on your BMR and is not healthy long term. Get a professional to help you and THEN you can log them into my fitness pal (if you have the patience, I personally don't). Sometimes healthy options are higher in calories than processed counterparts. So yes you CAN overconsume healthy food and sometimes the lower calorie option is better for your goals.
.
.
If health is the goal. We're mainly talking whole nutritious foods. We're talking very little processed food. We're thinking about our insides not just our outside 🙏 It's probably more a long term goal.
.
.
If performance is the goal our macro and micro nutrients become far more important. Are we getting enough protein for recovery? Do we have a good cárb fuel store? Are we using fats as an anti inflammatory? Are we eating enough fruit and veggies for our immune system?
.
.
Figure out your goal. Seek help from someone qualified. Get a coach. It's not as simple as it seems sometimes 🙊😏 #fitlife #fitlifestyle #fitliving #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitness #fitgirls #fitfam #irishfitfam

Does everyone listen to their body? 🤔
.
.
Are you recovering properly? 🤔
.
.
Are you sleeping enough? 🤔
.
.
Yes calories are important but if performance is your goal calories are a small part of a much bigger circle. There are soooo many different elements that can contribute to an athletes performance😱 Sometimes it's actually overwhelming
.
.
Am I eating enough calories? Do I need a lot of carbs? Is protein that important? How much water should I be drinking? What are micros? Is strength and conditioning really important? How much sleep is enough? How many rest days do I need? Is mobility essential? Should I be foam rolling more often? Are ice baths important? Is alcohol really that bad? ❓❓❓❓❓❓❓❓❓❓❓❓❓
.
.
Athletes these days have so much to think about. And that's before they take into account their own personal lives and jobs 😴😴😴 You need to listen to your body. You need to sleep. You need to relax. You need to recover properly and eliminate the risk of injury. You need to be able to talk to a coach and explain how you are feeling.
Remember, spórt is a hobby. While it's a massive part of your life. Don't let it control it👌 Enjoy it, don't feel like it's a chore. 💯
